Adult male and female pair (briefly seen perched together) - The female of this pair is very unique in that it's cap and front mustachial stripe are a burnt orange color; just slightly richer in color than the dark-orange of the bird's mantle. A typical 'Northern' female would have a blueish cap with dark orange on the very top of the head, and a black front mustachial stripe. The underside streaking of this kestrel is more finely patterned with darker, pointed markings that almost form loose barring across the front of the kestrel compared to the longer, and more blob-shaped streaks on a typical female. Tail patterns are highly variable among female kestrels, and this one has a fairly normal type with a thick subterminal bar and 6 thin inner tail bands. At first glance these unusual markings give the impression of a small female Eurasian Kestrel. Thanks to Kris Miller from Brogue, PA for alerting me to this awesome 'ginger' kestrel! She was actively hunting grasshoppers and offered some great photo opportunities.  Concerning what sort of genetic mutation may have caused this plumage anomaly, Jane Marlow (from National Aquarium) had this to say: "As far as a color mutation, a fully apheomelanistic (erythristic) bird would lack all black/gray pigment, leaving only red/red-brown pigment, while this bird retains black pigment (eumelanin) on its wings. While generally uncommon for birds to be erythristic only on an isolated part of the body, it's certainly not unheard of. A well-known example is the "opaline" mutation in budgerigars - these birds have reduced eumelanin on the head, while retaining its production on the rest of its body, albeit in a somewhat distorted pattern - very similar to a description of this bird's aberrant coloration! Falcons and parrots make up sister taxons, so it definitely makes you wonder if these mutations could be related."

Continuing, seen at close range along side trail off post #4. Bird seen perched, during which time it spent most of its time preening, and in flight close overhead and soaring higher. Medium-sized raptor, sleek and slender overall, long narrow wings in flight. P10 much shorter than P9 and P8 in flight. Body generally gray overall, with lighter gray head, small black mask around eyes, red iris. Long tail weakly banded. Underside of wings showing some brownish color and barring, flight feathers (including tertials) and tail generally browner than rest of body. At rest, small white splotches  visible on mantle and lower back. Second year bird, in heavy molt. Two-3 inner primaries missing (typical of second year bird), other primaries and secondaries heavily worn, retrices also quite worn. It seemed to have some kind of ailment or damage to its right eye; pupil never appeared to be entirely clear.

Locality: 4281 Bonita Beach Rd, Bonita Springs US-FL (26.3303,-81.8234)

Observation Details: This bird was reported without many details to Maine Audubon in the past day or so. Doug Hitchcox and Fyn Kynd followed up on this report and amazingly found the bird this morning. I arrived in the early afternoon and saw the bird after a brief scan at the intersection of King Street and The Ln. The bird was to the south-southwest over the trees along the Dennys River. It dropped out of sight; so I looked along Route 86 to the west. Shortly after crossing the Dennys River, I spotted the bird over the trees at the edge of a field and bordering the river.  This is one of those birds that is instantly recognizable by shape and pattern--an elegant long-winged raptor with a deeply forked tail. The upperparts and tail were blackish; the underparts, including entire head, were snowy white. In good light, I could see a darker, blackish bar across the leading portion of the upper wing. The secondaries seemed shiny and glossed with a slightly paler grayish bloom. There were times when these dark feathers of the upperwing seemed to be glossed purplish or bluish. Eventually, we saw the bird directly overhead at close range and could see small yellowish to pinkish-yellow feet, a dark gray bill with a pale gray to blue gray cere. The eyes were dark red. The underwing pattern was distinctive in being snowy white across the wing linings (lesser, median, and greater coverts of underwing). The rest of the wing, the remiges, were black, as was the entire tail.  The bird played on the wind as it hunted flying insects. The kite sometimes made rapid banks and turns to zero in on prey. I could not actually see any of the prey, but when the bird grabbed something (apparently) it reached forward with its feet and met them with its beak. It appeared to consume its prey on the wing. As photos show, these were small flying insects (not dragonflies or damselflies as far as I could tell). The bird seemed to find most of its prey over the tops of the trees, but occasionally much higher.  After meeting some locals, I learned that the bird had been seen by them since about September 7 (a rainy day that coincided with the remnants of hurricane Dorian passing east of here into Nova Scotia). This may be coincidence given other recent northerly Swallow-tailed Kites well away from the storms influence.

**RARE | Continuing bird first seen yesterday, 29 September 2016. I first found this bird in the northern  part of the airport sitting on the Medway Road fence line around 1350. The bird stayed on the airport side of Medway Road throughout the time I was there. When I left around 1615, the bird had moved closer to the airport offices, and was foraging out in the fields of the runway area.  Behavior: Would perch on fence or on ground. Hunted for most of the time I was there, successfully catching insects, typically grasshoppers, and other unidentified prey. Often would run on the ground, as well as flying down from a perch on the fence to capture prey. At one point the bird took off circled a few times gaining elevation, and plummeted in a dive. On 4 or 5 occasions, the bird would fly up to the fence directly in front of us, and allow for fantastic opportunities to study this bird up close. There no reason to approach rare birds beyond a respectable point, but this bird would fly in to distances that were much closer than I feel comfortable getting to a rare bird. It was an amazing experience with a stunning bird.

Observation Details: This is TBRC #1989-179, TPRF #833 and the same bird referred to in the 3rd ed. of the T.O.S. Checklist (1995) which listed it as a 1st accepted record for TX. Photos by Laurens Halsey.    From my notes, 4 of us flushed a small buteo from "a Huisache tree and it quickly disappeared around a bend in the road. It flew away with deep, fast wingbeats. We flushed it a second time when we rounded the bend, and this time it gave two or three calls and proceeded to rise on a thermal, circling higher and higher for several minutes. It ultimately disappeared" only to reappear a short time later "out of the west, gliding towards us down the road on flattened wings. It passed close overhead as if to return to where we had first flushed it. It then circled once or twice losing altitude, before banking toward the river and vanishing".   Location was "1/2 to 3/4 miles down the road in the ranch or just before the road opens up into the field". Last known sighting was Jul 28 (by whom I don't know). My notes of this "light morph sub-adult" bird include the following: "The underbody was completely white; that is the throat, breast, belly, and vent regions were clear of any streaks, bars, or smudges. The only dark body markings we discerned from below were the extensions of dark "cheek" patches which invaded down from the head and neck but stopped short of the throat.. This gave us the impression of a hood broken sharply at the throat. The tail seemed composed of two groups of feathers in different stages of wear or plumage..." etc. etc. I have more details available. We were certain of our ID and that Swainson's Hawk was eliminated. For one thing just by the way this hawk glided on flat wings.  At the time, Greg Lasley sent copies of the photos to Bill Clark, Brian Wheeler, Kenn Kaufman, and others and all concurred with the identification.

Susan Andres and I were driving south along the dam road, and looking east to a distant tall dead snag several hundred yards out, I saw what appeared to be a very blackish hawk-like bird perched near the top of the tree.  I put glass on it and was immediately struck by its very intense, overall blackish cast, which had a unique blueish tone and hints of earthy browns, that I have come to associate with Zone-tailed hawks.  I continued to look at the bird and Susan was able to get on it as well.  Though the hawk was pretty far out from us, we were both able to glean hints of its yellow legs and cere.  Details of the tail area were poorly seen from our vantage point.  I then noticed a second hawk perched nearby, which structurally seemed similar, but had a more brownish tone, grayish cere/bill area, unmarked brownish wings, with a darker cast to the center of the back and head, with a finely bared tail noted, giving the impression of a possible juvenile Zone-tailed.  I then obtained some photographs to further study and document the group.  At one point, there were two other birds associating with this one, but because of the distance, I can't say definitively if this was a family group or other hawk sp. like Swainson's. It was circling rather low on rising thermal current above a closed landfill and agricultural land. It was slowly moving in an eastern direction, while also going up in altitude. There were ravens flying near by as well. When I first observed it I thought it was a turkey vulture just based on overall shape and wing angles. I was doing biological work around the landfill at the time. I then saw that there wasn't the usual naked red head, and saw the white band on the tail with my naked eye. I quickly and excitedly got my binoculars and phone to take pictures (I was kicking myself for not having my canon camera with a longer lens!). I recognized it from my field guides, but had never seen it before in the field. I knew it was either a zone-tailed hawk or a black hawk. After referring to descriptions, pictures, and a range map, I knew with 100% certainty it was a rare occurrence of a zone-tailed hawk outside of even it's "rare" range in my Sibley guide. Being such a rare occurrence I decided it was very important that I add this data to the eBird/Cornell Lab database.

Spied a large white marked hawk on the ground some distance away over a berm and went marching quickly in the general direction it disappeared walking behind a large tumbleweed. It then took flight flushed by a dog walker and circled, sometimes hovering like a giant kestrel, and then circled at low elevation over to a snaggy eucalyptus in the center of the dog run area at south end of Fiesta Island.  It is a large very attractive looking hawk, milky and buffy white on the underparts with odd dark spots and arrows, large pale eye, fine brown streaked head, long yellow gape beneath eye.  Amazing upperparts coloration without rust red but instead with dark stone brown back and wings, darker subterminal banding on the flight feathers, and large milky white rump extending in pale coloration down the tail the end more colorfully marked. Pale whitish windows in the primaries. Very eye catching hawk - wow, wow, WOW! Got some amazing photos at close range.

Observation Details: Continuing bird; photos. Perched in dead tree in middle of field east of Beef Research Farm Rd. and south of Sugar Grove Rd. Compared to adjacent RTHA, and more barrel chested, big headed buteo with finely streaked head, dark eye line, white eyebrow above that, yellowish cere and gape; gape extending to eye; upperparts brownish gray with rusty edging on most feathers- centers of feathers dark but outer edges rusty; under parts white contrasting with spotting on lower breast and rusty barring on thighs and some barring on middle part of flanks; tail whitish gray with reddish tinges, especially when seen dorsally; when viewed ventrally the tail looks whitish with outer 1/2 a dull gray; bird flew from perch and returned; in flight, wings noticeable longer more tapered than adjacent RTHAs; underwings whitish but with conspicuous rusty mottling- darkish comma visible; rusty thighs contrasting with rest of underparts; in flight large white panels at base of primaries contrast with rest of dark wing; legs completely feathered to feet.

One very interesting bird with lots of rust underneath and a clear eye but seemingly adult-like plumage. Very interesting looking bird!! Addendum: I shared some photos with Jerry Liguori and he said it was an adult by plumage, but a younger adult. Plumage always trumps eye color, according to Jerry; and it can take Ferruginous Hawks longer to get the dark eye color than other buteos.
